## Relationship to the SQL-grounded audit

The existing SQL-grounded audit (`tools/cleanup_tier1/sql_grounded_audit.py`) grades **correctness** of non-trivial transformation cells against the producing SQL. It is silent on TRIVIAL rows because they have no math to validate.

The two concerns are orthogonal:

| | Math correct? | Math wrong? | No math (trivial) |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Has semantic** | both pass | math-audit FAIL | quality-grader pass |
| **No semantic** | quality-grader FAIL | both fail | quality-grader FAIL |

The math-audit pipeline is unchanged. The quality grader and climber-rewriter operate only on the bottom row.

## What is deliberately out of scope (in this phase)

| Out of scope | Why |
|--------------|-----|
| Sampling Databricks/Synapse for distribution stats | Explicit user constraint for this phase. Revisit if the climb exhausts at high rate. |
| Pulling Confluence / Atlassian knowledge | Same. |
| Inferring meaning from column name alone | Forbidden — high false-positive risk, the failure mode we are eliminating. |
| Inferring from sibling columns | Same. |
| Compressing already-good FK-with-enum rows | Different problem; deferred. |
| UC_generated wikis | Different table shape; deferred. |

## Acceptance criteria for this rule

- The TRIVIAL regex catalog above is **exhaustive** for the patterns in the current corpus. New trivial idioms discovered during Phase B grading are added here, not silently handled in code.
- The climber MUST emit, for every row it touches, a structured trace: `[(obj, col, transformation_cell, verdict)]` per hop. The trace is part of the audit artifact.
- The rewriter MUST NOT touch non-TRIVIAL rows.
- The rewriter MUST NOT silently drop the `(legacy …)` or `(alias …)` parentheticals when adopting an upstream terminal. If the original row had a bookkeeping parenthetical, append it after the adopted text: `{terminal} (via {upstream}; legacy — always 0 since 2019)`.
